WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.600
Hello, my name is Colin Rendell, and I'm a professor at Duke University in the Department

00:00:09.600 --> 00:00:10.960
of Statistical Science.

00:00:10.960 --> 00:00:14.480
I've been teaching data science with R for a decade now, and I've been teaching Shiny

00:00:14.480 --> 00:00:17.360
specifically to our students since 2015.

00:00:17.360 --> 00:00:20.600
This year at PositConf, I'm teaching a one-day workshop on getting started with Shiny for

00:00:20.600 --> 00:00:24.719
R that is targeted at current R users who are interested in learning Shiny for the very

00:00:24.719 --> 00:00:25.719
first time.

00:00:25.719 --> 00:00:29.040
Here are three reasons why you should consider taking this workshop.

00:00:29.040 --> 00:00:32.080
The first is building a solid foundation.

00:00:32.080 --> 00:00:36.439
While Shiny apps are written in R code, they use a reactive programming paradigm, which

00:00:36.439 --> 00:00:41.200
is very different from what most R users are experienced with when they're developing R

00:00:41.200 --> 00:00:42.759
code themselves.

00:00:42.759 --> 00:00:45.919
Throughout this workshop, we will help you develop a thorough understanding of this reactive

00:00:45.919 --> 00:00:50.959
paradigm, how you implement it, how you debug applications using it, so that you are prepared

00:00:50.959 --> 00:00:54.520
to write your own Shiny apps once you finish the workshop.

00:00:54.520 --> 00:00:56.840
We also want to help you putting it all together.

00:00:56.840 --> 00:00:59.840
Throughout the course of the day, we'll be working on the iterative development of a

00:00:59.840 --> 00:01:05.680
complete and real-world application that includes complex user interactions and internal functionality.

00:01:05.680 --> 00:01:10.160
We will be starting with a very basic app, and we will then be incrementally adding functionality

00:01:10.160 --> 00:01:15.559
and introducing new core concepts of Shiny along the way as we add features to that application.

00:01:15.559 --> 00:01:18.919
We'll take time to discuss how the added features interact with the existing functionality of

00:01:18.919 --> 00:01:23.080
the app, which is an incredibly important but often overlooked aspect of developing

00:01:23.080 --> 00:01:27.160
Shiny apps that is often hard to pick up from the documentation alone.

00:01:27.160 --> 00:01:32.199
Finally, active learning and live coding are going to be a big component of this workshop.

00:01:32.199 --> 00:01:35.800
We will definitely have a series of lecture components to this workshop, but we will be

00:01:35.800 --> 00:01:39.959
breaking those up by including interactive activities and exercises where you'll be asked

00:01:39.959 --> 00:01:42.800
to work on small parts of the larger application.

00:01:42.800 --> 00:01:46.239
There will also be regular live coding segments in which we will collaboratively work through

00:01:46.239 --> 00:01:50.680
the exercises, and in so doing, demonstrate best practices.

00:01:50.680 --> 00:01:55.959
We'll also narrate the process of implementing solutions, working through those solutions,

00:01:55.959 --> 00:01:59.239
and then also, when there's problems with those solutions, working through the process

00:01:59.239 --> 00:02:03.120
of debugging and troubleshooting so that you can solve them in the real world.

00:02:03.120 --> 00:02:07.279
If any of this sounds interesting to you, I would highly recommend going to posit.com

00:02:07.279 --> 00:02:11.160
slash conference to look into more details about this particular workshop and the other

00:02:11.160 --> 00:02:13.240
workshops that are being offered.

00:02:13.240 --> 00:02:15.320
From there, you'll be able to enroll in this or any of the others.

00:02:15.320 --> 00:02:17.160
I hope to see you in Chicago in September.

00:02:20.679 --> 00:02:21.679
Thank you.

00:02:21.679 --> 00:02:21.679


